IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: THE HEALTH TRUST AIMS TO IMPROVE HEALTH AND QUALITY OF LIFE FOR RESIDENTS OF THE GREATER PAJARO VALLEY BY PROVIDING HEALTH PROMOTION SERVICES AND DIABETES SELF-MANAGEMENT EDUCATION. ADDITIONALLY, WE CONVENE CROSS-SECTOR STAKEHOLDERS TO ALIGN RESOURCES TO REALIZE A SHARED VISION OF HEALTH AND PROVIDE GRANTS AND ALLIED SUPPORT TO LOCAL GROUPS ENSURING ACCESS TO HEALTH PROMOTION AND DISEASE PREVENTION PROGRAMS AS WELL AS QUALITY, CULTURALLY COMPETENT WHOLE PERSON HEALTHCARE.

IRS990.Desc: DIABETES HEALTH CENTER (DHC) - The Health Trust operates the Diabetes Health Center (DHC), a community-based health education and diabetes care program that provided culturally responsive, empowering disease self-management and health promotion education in 2,015 individual sessions and 26 workplace wellness, job site education and community outreach events this year benefiting 1,819 individuals.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: GRANT MAKING - The Health Trust awarded 17 grants totaling $205,000 to local nonprofits working to promote active living & healthy eating as cornerstones of health. Grant funds also strengthened nonprofit organizations that provide oral, physical and mental health care for those facing the greatest obstacles to care. Additionally, 12 students benefited from scholarship support to pursue careers in the health professions, fostering a local pipeline of ethnically diverse health professionals.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: LEADERSHIP - The Health Trust builds, sustains and leverages partnerships with peer nonprofits promoting health and well-being in the tri-county region encompassing parts of Santa Cruz, Monterey and San Benito Counties. The Health Trust leads the #LIVEPajaroValley Collective, a group of local nonprofits and public agencies actively fostering community engagement in decision-making that leads to a healthier community. We convene the Pajaro Valley Food, Farming & Health Policy Council, a cross-sector group working to create a local environment where the healthy choice is the easy choice for every resident. the Health Trust's Regional Diabetes Collaborative supports and coordinates efforts to prevent and manage diabetes. We are an active contributor of the Health Improvement Partnership of Santa Cruz County, a roundtable of healthcare leaders implementing collaborative solutions to priority issues affecting health equity and outcomes, especially for marginalized populations.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Part V, Line 4: Intended uses of the endowment fund.
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ENDOWMENT FUNDS ARE HELD IN ORDER TO GENERATE REVENUES IN SUPPORT OF HEALTH PROGRAMS FOR SENIORS AND CHILDREN, DENTAL NEEDS OF THOSE IN THE PAJARO VALLEY AND FOR THE UNRESTRICTED USE OF THE TRUST.

As a tax-exempt not-for-profit organization, the Organization is exempt from federal income tax under Section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code and from state franchise tax under California Revenue and Taxation Code Section 23701(d), but is subject to taxes on unrelated business income when earned. Management has considered its tax positions and believes that all of the positions taken in its federal and state exempt organization tax returns are more likely than not to be sustained upon examination. The Organizations returns are subject to examination by federal and state taxing authorities, generally for three year and four years, respectively, after they are filed.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Grantmaker's Description of How Grants are Used
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: ALL ORGANIZATIONS APPLYING FOR FUNDING MUST SUBMIT A DETAILED LINE-ITEM BUDGET, INCLUDING INCOME AND EXPENSES FOR THE PROPOSED PROJECT. THEY MUST INDICATE THE AMOUNT PROPOSED FOR FUNDING FROM THE TRUST BY LINE ITEM AND INCLUDE NOTES FOR ANY LINE ITEMS THAT REQUIRE ADDITIONAL EXPLANATION.IF APPROVED FOR FUNDING, GRANTEES MUST SIGN A GRANT CONTRACT IN WHICH THEY AGREE TO USE THE GRANT FUNDS TO ACCOMPLISH THE SPECIFIC OUTCOMES OUTLINED IN THEIR GRANT PROPOSAL. THEY ALSO AGREE TO INFORM THE TRUST IMMEDIATELY IF THEY ARE UNABLE TO PERFORM ON ANY ASPECT OF THE GRANT CONTRACT ACTIVITIES AS OUTLINED IN THE PROPOSAL. THE CONTRACT INDICATES THAT USE OF THESE FUNDS FOR ANY PURPOSE OTHER THAN SET FORTH IN THE GRANT PROPOSAL AND/OR FAILURE TO REPORT CHANGES IMMEDIATELY OR TO PERFORM ON THE CONTRACT OUTCOMES MAY RESULT IN FORFEITURE OF PART OR ALL OF THE GRANT AMOUNT. ALSO REQUIRE GRANTEES TO SUBMIT PROGRESS AND FINAL REPORTS IN WHICH THEY MUST PROVIDE A DETAILED PROGRAM BUDGET THAT COMPARES ACTUAL EXPENDITURES TO THE APPROVED BUDGET.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 11b: Form 990 Review Process
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Pajaro Valley Community Health Trust engages a CPA firm to assist with the preparation and filing of the Form 990, based on an audit engagement completed by the same CPA firm. Once the CPA firm has completed a draft of the form 990, a copy will be sent to the Board of Directors for review and approval before the tax return is filed.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 15a: Compensation Review & Approval Process - CEO, Top Management
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: FOR CEO AND TOP FINANCIAL PERSON, EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE COMPARES COMPENSATION WITH SIMILAR ORGANIZATIONS LOCALLY AND NATIONALLY; SALARY INCREASES ARE BASED ON COMPENSATION AND PERFORMANCE BASED. EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE EVALUATES CEO'S PERFORMANCE AND MAKES RECOMMENDATIONS TO THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS FOR APPROVAL, ANNUALLY, WITHIN BUDGETARY PARAMETERS.
